      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates QoI change <2% between medium and fine mesh densities for all three solvers.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted for each FEA code. Stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement all converged within 1.5% between medium and fine meshes. Richardson extrapolation confirmed discretization uncertainty contributions are negligible relative to experimental variability."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals and energy balance checks confirm numerical solution accuracy to within 0.1% for all load steps.",
      "rationale": "All analyses used direct sparse solvers with tight force and displacement residual tolerances (1e-6 relative). Energy balance was monitored at each load increment; no artificial energy dissipation was detected. Achieved level 2 comfortably satisfies the required level 1."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent analyst review of model setup, boundary conditions, and material assignments for each FEA code; documented in analysis plan prior to execution.",
      "rationale": "Each FEA model was independently reviewed by a second analyst before execution. Boundary conditions (fixed inferior vertebral body, displacement-controlled superior loading point per F1717 geometry), material assignments (Ti-6Al-4V screw, UHMWPE vertebral body surrogate), and contact definitions were verified against the test protocol. No discrepancies were identified."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Linear elastic material model with isotropic properties justified for Ti-6Al-4V below yield; contact formulation captures screw-rod and screw-vertebral body interactions.",
      "rationale": "The compression-bending regime below yield is well-described by linear elastic constitutive models for Ti-6Al-4V. Nonlinear contact between screw, rod, and vertebral body surrogate is captured via penalty-based contact with friction coefficient calibrated from literature. Model form uncertainty is bounded by the ensemble spread across three independent implementations."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from MMPDS and supplier certificates; geometry from CMM-measured as-built dimensions of tested constructs; all inputs documented with traceability.",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus (114 GPa) and Poisson ratio (0.34) for Ti-6Al-4V taken from MMPDS-11. UHMWPE surrogate properties from ISO 5834. Construct geometry inputs were derived from coordinate measuring machine measurements of the actual test specimens, ensuring model inputs reflect as-built rather than nominal dimensions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N=11 constructs from production lots, assembled per clinical technique, with CMM-verified geometry; sample size sufficient for statistical comparison per ASME V&V 40 guidance.",
      "rationale": "Eleven constructs were assembled from production-representative lots of the 7.5 mm non-cannulated pedicle screw system using the surgeon-specified torque protocol. CMM measurements confirmed dimensional conformance. Sample size supports computation of mean and standard deviation for all three QoIs with adequate statistical power for the E/uval metric."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions replicate the mechanical loading environment of the COU; multiple load levels or configurations evaluated.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single F1717 compression-bending configuration at room temperature per the standard protocol. While the standard loading condition is well-controlled and clinically representative, only one test condition (load angle, offset distance) was evaluated. This limits the factor to achieved level 2, one below the required level 3. This deficiency is noted and accepted given that F1717 specifies a single standardized condition."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA model inputs (geometry, material, boundary conditions, loading) demonstrated to be equivalent to experimental test inputs within documented tolerances.",
      "rationale": "A parameter-by-parameter equivalency table was prepared comparing FEA inputs to experimental measurements. Geometry: CMM-measured dimensions used directly. Material: certified lot properties used. Loading: displacement rate and load application point matched. Boundary conditions: vertebral body surrogate fixity reproduced in FEA via rigid constraint. All parameters within ±2% of experimental values."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval < 1.96 and percent difference <10% for all three QoIs across all three FEA codes.",
      "rationale": "For stiffness: mean FEA 487 N/mm vs. experimental 501±18 N/mm; E/uval=0.78, difference 2.8%. For yield force: mean FEA 1243 N vs. experimental 1267±41 N; E/uval=0.59, difference 1.9%. For force at 40 mm: mean FEA 892 N vs. experimental 921±35 N; E/uval=0.83, difference 3.1%. All metrics satisfy pre-established acceptance criteria across all three solvers."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are directly linked to the COU decision (structural adequacy of the pedicle screw construct) and are mechanistically relevant to the failure modes of concern.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness governs load sharing with adjacent spinal segments; yield force defines the safety margin against permanent deformation; force at 40 mm displacement characterizes post-yield behavior relevant to worst-case clinical loading. All three QoIs are standard F1717 outputs and are directly relevant to the regulatory decision on structural adequacy."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities (F1717 bench testing of production constructs) are sufficiently similar to the COU (FEA-supported design verification of the same construct family) to support credibility inference.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity uses the same screw design, same rod diameter, same assembly protocol, and the same standardized test method as the design verification context. The FEA models validated here are the same model instances used for the regulatory submission. The multi-laboratory design (two independent test sites) and multi-solver ensemble (three independent FEA implementations) strengthen the relevance inference."
